So Yaroslav also married
one of his own daughters

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:35.790
to the king of Norway, right?

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.040
So we're very, here, connected

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:41.340
to the history of Scandinavia.

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:43.830
And it's inconceivable
that he didn't speak

00:12:43.830 --> 00:12:45.840
whatever we wanna call
the Swedish language,

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:48.513
or whatever we wanna call it at that time.

00:12:50.220 --> 00:12:52.500
He did marry another one of his daughters,

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:53.610
this is just something we have to know.

00:12:53.610 --> 00:12:55.770
He did marry one of his other daughters

00:12:55.770 --> 00:12:59.280
to the king of France,
which is a fun fact,

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:01.080
which every Ukrainian
needs for you to know.

00:13:01.080 --> 00:13:03.780
So we're gonna make sure
that it's in this class.

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:06.330
That would be Yaroslav's favorite daughter

00:13:06.330 --> 00:13:10.260
who was called Ana, who was
remembered as Anne of Kyiv.

00:13:10.260 --> 00:13:12.000
Because from the point of view of Paris,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.179
she was Anne of Kyiv.

00:13:14.179 --> 00:13:16.591
She, in the middle of the 11th century,

00:13:16.591 --> 00:13:19.080
she was the queen of France.

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:21.150
She was the one who
went to Paris and said,

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:24.510
compared to Kyiv, this is
kind of dingy and pathetic

00:13:24.510 --> 00:13:25.620
and wanted to go back.

00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:28.593
So now you know, that's Anne of Kyiv.

00:13:29.442 --> 00:13:34.200
So Yaroslav is a Scandinavian prince,

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:39.200
but he is also an inheritor
of Byzantine Christianity

00:13:40.110 --> 00:13:41.130
from his father.

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:44.010
And he is also the ruler of
a Slavic speaking population.

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:45.960
So it's like there's a triangle.

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:49.530
So on the Byzantine side
of the triangle, he builds,

00:13:49.530 --> 00:13:53.613
or maybe he completes
the church of San Sophia,

00:13:54.584 --> 00:13:58.560
which is the central cathedral in Kyiv,

00:13:58.560 --> 00:13:59.760
which still exists.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:03.480
It exists in a kind in a kind
of Baroque reconstruction,

00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:05.580
but which still exists and was completed

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:08.970
somewhere around the 1030s.

00:14:08.970 --> 00:14:12.450
And it was modeled on Hagiya
Sophia in Constantinople.

00:14:12.450 --> 00:14:14.400
So the main cathedral
in Kyiv was modeled on

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:18.090
the main cathedral in Constantinople.

00:14:18.090 --> 00:14:20.880
So he's balancing that.

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:24.870
With that church came
Greek speaking priests.

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:27.743
The first priests who came
to convert the population

00:14:27.743 --> 00:14:29.902
were from Constantinople.

00:14:29.902 --> 00:14:32.790
They spoke Greek.

00:14:32.790 --> 00:14:35.940
And with these Greek priests,
and with the conversion

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:37.710
came a certain model of order,

00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:39.979
which might seem
intuitive to a lot of you.

00:14:39.979 --> 00:14:42.570
It seems so natural, perhaps because

00:14:42.570 --> 00:14:44.640
it's now more or less hegemonic,

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:47.100
but it had to arrive at a certain point,

00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:48.742
which is the days of the week.

00:14:48.742 --> 00:14:52.053
The days of the week and the
idea that the day of rest

00:14:52.053 --> 00:14:56.340
is the seventh day, Sunday.

00:14:56.340 --> 00:15:00.540
Churches and churchyards
come with Christianity.

00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:03.870
The idea that you bury your
dead, as I mentioned before,

00:15:03.870 --> 00:15:06.300
rather than cremate
comes with Christianity.

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:08.040
That you bury them in a certain place,

00:15:08.040 --> 00:15:11.370
a cemetery in a churchyard,
comes with Christianity.

00:15:11.370 --> 00:15:13.620
So there's a civilizational package,

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:15.360
which comes with the Greek priests.

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:19.260
But interestingly, it is
Yaroslav who shifts over

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:24.260
from Greek priests to local,
Slavic speaking priests.

00:15:24.630 --> 00:15:28.680
In the year 1051, he
manages to have appointed,

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:32.220
or appoints himself, as the
local head of the church,

00:15:32.220 --> 00:15:36.330
the metropolitan, a man called Helarion,

00:15:36.330 --> 00:15:39.660
who was a local Slav and not a Greek.

00:15:39.660 --> 00:15:42.270
And somewhere around this time as well,

00:15:42.270 --> 00:15:46.890
and this is crucial, the
language of the liturgy

00:15:46.890 --> 00:15:51.890
gets changed from Greek
to old church Slavonic.

00:15:53.370 --> 00:15:56.277
So in other words,

00:15:56.277 --> 00:15:59.670
there's a big difference
between going to church

00:15:59.670 --> 00:16:03.180
and hearing a language that
you can't understand at all,

00:16:03.180 --> 00:16:05.130
to going to church and hearing a language

00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:08.160
where you can understand
a little bit, right?

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:10.650
So that's basically the shift from Greek

00:16:10.650 --> 00:16:12.660
to old church Slavonic.

00:16:12.660 --> 00:16:15.390
Geek, from the point of view of Kyiv,

00:16:15.390 --> 00:16:16.920
is a foreign language.

00:16:16.920 --> 00:16:18.660
Very few people speak Greek.

00:16:18.660 --> 00:16:22.410
They're mostly people who have
arrived from Constantinople

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:24.720
or Greek traders coming up and down

00:16:24.720 --> 00:16:27.690
from the Black Sea coast,
as we've talked about,

00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:29.220
it's basically a foreign language.

00:16:29.220 --> 00:16:32.970
And in the whole history
of the Greek church,

00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:35.400
the Orthodox church, the
Eastern church in Kyiv,

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:38.222
relatively few people learn Greek.

00:16:38.222 --> 00:16:39.240
Some people do, but relatively few.

00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:42.060
Basically very educated
churchmen learn Greek.

00:16:42.060 --> 00:16:44.790
Old church Slavonic is a different story.

00:16:44.790 --> 00:16:46.530
You'll remember where old
church Slavonic came from.

00:16:46.530 --> 00:16:48.720
Old church Slavonic is invented
by Cyril and Methodius.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:50.550
It has this journey down to Bulgaria,

00:16:50.550 --> 00:16:52.710
and now it arrives in Kyiv.

00:16:52.710 --> 00:16:57.360
And it has the huge advantage
that it is a Slavic language.

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:01.140
It is based on a Slavic language,

00:17:01.140 --> 00:17:03.791
probably the Slavic language
that was spoken in Macedonia

00:17:03.791 --> 00:17:07.290
by the mother of Cyril and Methodius.

00:17:07.290 --> 00:17:09.600
But it's based in a Slavic language.

00:17:09.600 --> 00:17:12.930
And therefore, if you're a native speaker

00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:16.500
of a Slavic language, you
can figure out a lot of it.

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:18.390
So when I studied old,
I'm not a native speaker

00:17:18.390 --> 00:17:20.910
of Slavic language, but I
studied old church Slavonic.

00:17:20.910 --> 00:17:24.450
A lot of it was intuitive to
me, a thousand years later

00:17:24.450 --> 00:17:26.820
and with the funny glycolytic alphabet,

00:17:26.820 --> 00:17:28.680
but a lot of it was intuitive to me.

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:32.040
I could look at it and see a lot of it.

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:35.820
So it's not totally impenetrable and,

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:37.860
once you start with a Slavic language,

00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:39.420
and this is very important,

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:41.580
you can then start to mess with it.

00:17:41.580 --> 00:17:44.250
You can then take it as a
basis of a written language.

00:17:44.250 --> 00:17:48.580
And then with time,
vernacular words will start

00:17:49.464 --> 00:17:50.297
to make their way into the language.

00:17:50.297 --> 00:17:51.775
What's the vernacular?

00:17:51.775 --> 00:17:54.480
The vernacular is the language
as we actually speak it.

00:17:54.480 --> 00:17:55.860
As we actually speak it.

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:59.670
And so Slavic words, as
people actually spoke them,

00:17:59.670 --> 00:18:02.940
made their way into the written language,

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:06.240
thereby enriching it and changing it.

00:18:06.240 --> 00:18:09.360
And this language, church Slavonic,

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:12.060
slowly becomes a written language,

00:18:12.060 --> 00:18:14.460
which is serving not just the church,

00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:16.290
but also the state.

00:18:16.290 --> 00:18:18.180
And this is hugely important because,

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:21.870
if you're going to run a state
as distinct from a church,

00:18:21.870 --> 00:18:22.860
it's good to have law.

00:18:22.860 --> 00:18:23.850
It's good to have a language in which

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:25.080
you can record that law.

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:28.290
So old church Slavonic, in
the version that it's used

00:18:28.290 --> 00:18:32.970
in the Kyivan state, is usually
called Chancery Slavonic.

00:18:32.970 --> 00:18:35.220
Just to make this distinction.

00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:36.873
Chancery Slavonic.

00:18:42.067 --> 00:18:44.820
And this Chancery Slavonic is recorded in,

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:47.100
is the language of a very important text,

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:49.710
which seems to originate with Yaroslav,

00:18:49.710 --> 00:18:52.770
and then continues after his
time for another century or so,

00:18:52.770 --> 00:18:55.800
which is called the Ruska
Pravda, or the Russkaya Pravda,

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:59.970
which is a collection of laws.

00:18:59.970 --> 00:19:01.740
So there's secular law now.

00:19:01.740 --> 00:19:03.150
There's secular law.

00:19:03.150 --> 00:19:06.540
Not just church custom and
church law, but secular law.

00:19:06.540 --> 00:19:11.540
And what the law itself says
is itself very revealing.

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:15.330
So now the law becomes a
historical source for us.

00:19:15.330 --> 00:19:16.620
We don't just have sagas,

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:18.910
we don't just have genealogies,

00:19:18.910 --> 00:19:21.678
we don't just have, you know,

00:19:21.678 --> 00:19:23.040
legends about Rus' written in Kyiv

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:24.390
a century after the events.

00:19:24.390 --> 00:19:27.330
We have the law, which was
applied in its own time.

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:29.587
What we see in this law are at least two

00:19:29.587 --> 00:19:31.800
very important developments.

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:35.100
Number one, you see that
the society has shifted

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:37.620
from the kind of society we
talked about in the beginning,

00:19:37.620 --> 00:19:40.740
which is one where
people could be enslaved,

00:19:40.740 --> 00:19:43.290
to one in which the chief
preoccupation of people

00:19:43.290 --> 00:19:46.980
was agriculture, and
agriculture is being regulated.

00:19:46.980 --> 00:19:50.190
So we now have a state which is based upon

00:19:50.190 --> 00:19:54.630
people generating a
surplus in agriculture.

00:19:54.630 --> 00:19:57.360
The classic model, which
we see over and over again,

00:19:57.360 --> 00:19:59.400
beginning in Mesopotamia,

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:01.890
the classic model, where
you can have a city,

00:20:01.890 --> 00:20:04.440
and you can have a state
with a capital in that city,

00:20:04.440 --> 00:20:08.370
because you have rules about
how you collect a surplus

00:20:08.370 --> 00:20:11.250
from the people who are
actually working the land.

00:20:11.250 --> 00:20:13.050
Which may be a somewhat
exploitative system,

00:20:13.050 --> 00:20:15.390
but it's a very different
system than raiding

00:20:15.390 --> 00:20:16.980
and slave trading.

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:19.260
It's a very different system
than raiding and slave trading.

00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:21.960
And it describes a
relationship between a ruler

00:20:21.960 --> 00:20:24.750
and his people, as opposed
to a relationship between

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:27.570
people who are just passing
through and collecting things

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:29.610
or people that they're going to sell

00:20:29.610 --> 00:20:30.930
somewhere further down the river.

00:20:30.930 --> 00:20:32.880
So by the time the law is written down,

00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:34.740
that transition has been achieved

00:20:34.740 --> 00:20:37.650
and we're in a different kind of society.

00:20:37.650 --> 00:20:39.120
Maybe even more fundamentally,

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:42.150
what you see in the Russkaya
Pravda, the Ruska Pravda,

00:20:42.150 --> 00:20:44.160
is an attempt to make a transition

00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:47.915
from a culture of personal revenge,

00:20:47.915 --> 00:20:52.915
to a culture where disputes
are actually settled in courts.

00:20:53.340 --> 00:20:55.770
So I'm sure all of you,
you know, in your lives,

00:20:55.770 --> 00:20:57.810
depending upon where you're
from, have some familiarity,

00:20:57.810 --> 00:20:59.610
at least from, I don't know, film,

00:20:59.610 --> 00:21:03.540
with what I mean by personal revenge.

00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:05.580
Where I do something to your clan

00:21:05.580 --> 00:21:07.590
and therefore your clan has
to do something to my clan,

00:21:07.590 --> 00:21:09.823
and this can go on indefinitely,
and it can be very costly

00:21:09.823 --> 00:21:11.700
and destabilizing.

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:13.530
If you're trying to set up a state,

00:21:13.530 --> 00:21:15.420
you don't want this clan and this clan

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:18.360
to have a feud indefinitely, right?

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:20.940
If there's a dispute, like
this clan has stolen this,

00:21:20.940 --> 00:21:23.220
or this clan has burned
down that, or whatever,

00:21:23.220 --> 00:21:24.690
you want that dispute to come to me,

00:21:24.690 --> 00:21:26.580
you want the dispute to come to the court,

00:21:26.580 --> 00:21:28.170
to the state, where it can be resolved.

00:21:28.170 --> 00:21:30.420
And so one of the things
that Ruska Pravda lays down

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:32.731
is what the appropriate penalties are.

00:21:32.731 --> 00:21:37.731
So there's a generic penalty
rather than personal feuds,

00:21:38.310 --> 00:21:41.223
this is the kind of thing
that builds up a state.

00:21:42.562 --> 00:21:45.840
But, I keep coming back to this,

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:50.840
but a weakness in the state
is that it didn't have

00:21:51.450 --> 00:21:54.543
the legal structures to allow
it to perpetuate itself,

00:21:54.543 --> 00:21:58.080
which one finds surprisingly
often is a problem with states.

00:21:58.080 --> 00:22:00.690
It's actually, it's kind of
the magic of founding a state

00:22:00.690 --> 00:22:03.630
is how, the German sociologist Max Weber

00:22:03.630 --> 00:22:04.950
was also obsessed with this,

00:22:04.950 --> 00:22:07.920
how you get from the
stage of founding a state

00:22:07.920 --> 00:22:09.930
to the stage of continuing a state.

00:22:09.930 --> 00:22:12.630
Where you might found
a state because of some

00:22:12.630 --> 00:22:15.330
great achievement or because
of some charismatic leader,

00:22:15.330 --> 00:22:17.722
but neither the achievement
nor the charisma lasts.

00:22:17.722 --> 00:22:21.960
And so then how do you keep
the state actually going?

00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:23.430
Maybe you found institutions,

00:22:23.430 --> 00:22:25.170
these institutions sound pretty good,

00:22:25.170 --> 00:22:27.180
but how do you make sure
that people continue

00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:29.310
to believe in them without the achievement

00:22:29.310 --> 00:22:32.246
and the charisma somehow backing them up?

00:22:32.246 --> 00:22:34.860
In then you event, how can
you do it without a procedure?

00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:38.070
So, in Kyiv, when we
talk about Kyivan Rus,

00:22:38.070 --> 00:22:42.510
we're talking about a range
of lands, going to the east,

00:22:42.510 --> 00:22:45.090
going to the north,
going a bit to the south

00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:46.350
and west of Kyiv.

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:48.600
We're talking about not
just Kyiv and Ukraine today,

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:51.246
we're talking about what's now Belarus

00:22:51.246 --> 00:22:53.550
and what's now a lot of European Russia.

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:57.300
All the way up to a bit to
the east of what's now Moscow.

00:22:57.300 --> 00:23:00.150
And these various
districts were passed out

00:23:00.150 --> 00:23:03.360
to the various sons in an
extremely confusing order,

00:23:03.360 --> 00:23:05.523
which honestly no one has figured out.

00:23:06.764 --> 00:23:08.370
And one suspects it changed
from generation to generation,

00:23:08.370 --> 00:23:10.230
or sometimes that they
were just making it up.

00:23:10.230 --> 00:23:13.830
And if we don't know it, I
think it's forgivable because

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:16.020
whatever the rules were, the brothers

00:23:16.020 --> 00:23:18.720
were constantly fighting each other.

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:20.430
And if they were constantly
fighting each other,

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:22.110
it means that whatever the rules were,

00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:24.660
maybe they were contested, or not clear,

00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:27.030
or maybe not taken always seriously.

00:23:27.030 --> 00:23:31.410
So the rulers in Kyiv passed
out the various districts

00:23:31.410 --> 00:23:34.020
to their sons, and there was
an idea that a certain son

00:23:34.020 --> 00:23:35.730
at some point would
become the ruler of Kyiv

00:23:35.730 --> 00:23:37.140
and will be superior to all the others,

00:23:37.140 --> 00:23:39.330
but that never panned out the way that

00:23:39.330 --> 00:23:40.560
it was supposed to be.

00:23:40.560 --> 00:23:43.950
So after Yaroslav's death in 1054,

00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:46.200
we essentially have one long confusing

00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:50.043
series of succession crises
until the Mongols come in 1241.

00:23:52.560 --> 00:23:55.890
There are however, at
least one moment in here

00:23:55.890 --> 00:23:57.630
which I want you to mark,

00:23:57.630 --> 00:24:01.500
which is the rise of a
city called Vladimir,

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:03.090
not the person, the city.

00:24:03.090 --> 00:24:07.500
And we're gonna call it
Vladimir and not Volodymyr

00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:10.800
because this city is all the way out in

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:14.317
the far Eastern extreme of Rus',

00:24:14.317 --> 00:24:17.430
a little bit to the east
of where Moscow now is.

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:21.543
I say now, because Moscow
didn't exist at the time.

00:24:22.470 --> 00:24:27.470
Vladimir, the city, was
ruled in the 1160s, 1170s

00:24:28.860 --> 00:24:31.470
by a man called Andrey Bogolyubsky,

00:24:31.470 --> 00:24:34.560
who I think is on your list,
should be on your list.

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:37.830
And he attacked Kyiv, not once, but twice.

00:24:37.830 --> 00:24:39.510
The first time he successfully sacked it.

00:24:39.510 --> 00:24:42.390
The second time he was repulsed.

00:24:42.390 --> 00:24:45.780
But the point is that Andrey Bogolyubsky

00:24:45.780 --> 00:24:49.110
had the idea that he
was gonna make Vladimir

00:24:49.110 --> 00:24:52.590
the most important city, the
successor of Kyiv, as it were.

00:24:52.590 --> 00:24:55.200
He took an important
icon that was near Kyiv,

00:24:55.200 --> 00:24:57.000
and he brought it to Vladimir.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:58.620
He built a church in Vladimir,

00:24:58.620 --> 00:25:02.280
which was meant to look
like St. Sophia in Kyiv.

00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:04.800
So he had the idea that he would
be the most important ruler

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:08.760
and that his city would be
more important than Kyiv.

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:12.093
So this is Vladimir, and
Vladimir is in a district

00:25:12.093 --> 00:25:14.583
which is called Suzdal.

00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:21.420
The Mongols are going to come,

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:23.010
they're going to wipe out Vladimir,

00:25:23.010 --> 00:25:24.300
they're gonna wipe out Suzdal,

00:25:24.300 --> 00:25:25.920
they're gonna wipe out
basically everything

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:27.570
in that part of Rus.

00:25:27.570 --> 00:25:30.000
But I want you to at
least mark that this idea

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.760
was already here in the 12th century,

00:25:32.760 --> 00:25:34.710
that there could be a successor to Kyiv

00:25:34.710 --> 00:25:37.230
that could somehow be better than Kyiv.

00:25:37.230 --> 00:25:38.460
Okay.

00:25:38.460 --> 00:25:40.980
When the Mongols do come,
and we'll talk more about

00:25:40.980 --> 00:25:42.330
the Mongols and what they were up to,

00:25:42.330 --> 00:25:47.040
but when the Mongols do come,
we see a partition of Rus,

00:25:47.040 --> 00:25:49.020
which is very durable.

00:25:49.020 --> 00:25:50.280
I'll just say a word about the Mongols

00:25:50.280 --> 00:25:51.522
and what they were up to.

00:25:51.522 --> 00:25:52.803
Just a word.

00:25:53.730 --> 00:25:56.040
It is always the case that
from the point of view

00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:59.040
of the people whose cities get sacked,

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:03.090
that the arriving people
are just marauders,

00:26:03.090 --> 00:26:04.650
and chaotic and so on,

00:26:04.650 --> 00:26:07.650
but it is almost always
the case that, in fact,

00:26:07.650 --> 00:26:09.720
what is happening is that
those who are arriving

00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:11.820
are trying to establish trade routes,

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:13.890
admittedly on terms favorable to them.

00:26:13.890 --> 00:26:15.390
And you tend to get, I mean,

00:26:15.390 --> 00:26:17.670
this is why we now have a
European Union to avoid this,

00:26:17.670 --> 00:26:20.010
but the way you get terms favorable to you

00:26:20.010 --> 00:26:21.480
is you sack the city.

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:24.090
And then you get terms favorable to you.

00:26:24.090 --> 00:26:26.010
I mean, it's tough, but that's how it is.

00:26:26.010 --> 00:26:29.100
So the Mongols, like
the Vikings before them,

00:26:29.100 --> 00:26:31.620
were trying to establish
a long trade route,

00:26:31.620 --> 00:26:34.170
the Vikings over sea,
the Mongols over land,

00:26:34.170 --> 00:26:37.080
in which they would be
able to trade favorably

00:26:37.080 --> 00:26:38.370
all the way down the line

00:26:38.370 --> 00:26:40.470
at terms which are favorable to them.

00:26:40.470 --> 00:26:41.760
At terms which are favorable to them.

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:45.120
And they had tremendous success with this

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:46.170
everywhere they went.

00:26:47.100 --> 00:26:48.690
They were never really defeated.

00:26:48.690 --> 00:26:52.980
In the early 1240s, they
destroy what remains

00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:54.510
of Kyivan Rus'.

00:26:54.510 --> 00:26:56.700
You understand that when
they destroy Kyivan Rus',

00:26:56.700 --> 00:26:58.800
they're not destroying a unified state,

00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:00.600
because there is no unified state.

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:03.222
There are a bunch of
districts with rivals.

00:27:03.222 --> 00:27:08.222
When the princes of Rus'
go out to meet the Mongols

00:27:09.480 --> 00:27:11.880
on the battlefield, they're literally

00:27:11.880 --> 00:27:15.390
arguing amongst one another
on the way to the battlefield

00:27:15.390 --> 00:27:17.100
about who is who, and
who gets to go first,

00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:17.970
and who's the most important.

00:27:17.970 --> 00:27:19.953
So that gives you a sense.

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:22.920
Even if they'd have been
in perfect formation,

00:27:22.920 --> 00:27:24.390
had loved one another, they still would've

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:26.220
had their hats handed them
by the Mongols, however.

00:27:26.220 --> 00:27:27.960
The Mongols were gonna win.

00:27:27.960 --> 00:27:30.000
So after the Mongol invasion,

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.210
we get a kind of three part division

00:27:33.210 --> 00:27:36.000
of the lands of old Rus,
which I'm gonna mark.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.640
And then we're gonna talk about
the most important of these,

00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:40.380
which is Lithuania.

00:27:40.380 --> 00:27:45.180
So, far off to the west
you have a district

00:27:45.180 --> 00:27:47.157
called Galicia-Volhynia.

00:27:47.157 --> 00:27:49.890
And that district, Galicia-Volhynia,

00:27:49.890 --> 00:27:51.960
is going to have a slightly
different trajectory

00:27:51.960 --> 00:27:54.430
than the rest, because Galicia-Volhynia

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:56.580
is gonna be ruled by its
own princes for a while.

00:27:56.580 --> 00:27:59.490
And then the Galician
part of Galicia-Volhynia

00:27:59.490 --> 00:28:03.420
is gonna become part of Poland
in the mid 14th century.

00:28:03.420 --> 00:28:05.820
So that Western part of Ukraine,

00:28:05.820 --> 00:28:07.890
Galicia-Volhynia, is going to have

00:28:07.890 --> 00:28:08.940
a somewhat different history.

00:28:08.940 --> 00:28:10.293
That's part one.

00:28:11.310 --> 00:28:13.983
Part two, so that's the extreme west,

00:28:14.850 --> 00:28:19.833
part two is the extreme east
or the extreme Northeast.

00:28:20.730 --> 00:28:24.210
Suzdal, the areas around what is gonna be

00:28:24.210 --> 00:28:25.230
at some point, Moscow.

00:28:25.230 --> 00:28:27.660
Moscow has still not come
into being, but I promise you,

00:28:27.660 --> 00:28:29.518
at some point Moscow will be created.

00:28:29.518 --> 00:28:33.175
The territories in Suzdal in the Northeast

00:28:33.175 --> 00:28:38.175
are going to remain longer
under direct Mongol domination.

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:41.070
That's also a different political story.

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:43.950
The Mongols are gonna come
and they're gonna stay.

00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:46.170
And they're gonna establish a durable form

00:28:46.170 --> 00:28:51.170
of transactional politics with the

00:28:51.210 --> 00:28:54.570
inheritors of Rus' princes
in the far Northeast.

00:28:54.570 --> 00:28:57.280
And we'll pick up that story next time

00:28:58.221 --> 00:29:00.750
when I talk about the
origins of the state,

00:29:00.750 --> 00:29:04.230
which is based in Moscow,
the origins of Russia.

00:29:04.230 --> 00:29:06.120
The third and the most
important trajectory

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:07.860
is the one we're going to follow today,

00:29:07.860 --> 00:29:11.310
which is the grand Duchy of Lithuania.

00:29:11.310 --> 00:29:14.340
Most of the territory of old Rus'

00:29:14.340 --> 00:29:17.760
comes under the grand Duchy of Lithuania.

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:21.540
And not only that, one of
the reasons why I've spent

00:29:21.540 --> 00:29:24.150
so much time talking about
this civilization is that,

00:29:24.150 --> 00:29:27.600
interestingly, this civilizational package

00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:30.690
associated with Yaroslav, the language,

00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:32.395
the Chancery Slavonic, the law

00:29:32.395 --> 00:29:34.980
all gets absorbed by Lithuania.

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:36.430
The Lithuanians take it over.

00:29:37.290 --> 00:29:39.450
They appropriate it,
they make it their own

00:29:39.450 --> 00:29:40.500
very comfortably.

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:45.030
And so in that sense, the
Kyivan civilization survives

00:29:45.030 --> 00:29:47.100
in the written form of its law.

00:29:47.100 --> 00:29:49.770
So it's sometimes it's
helpful to think of history

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:52.260
as having different speeds, or different

00:29:52.260 --> 00:29:55.080
elements in history having
different kinds of durability.

00:29:55.080 --> 00:29:56.970
So a language has a lot of durability.

00:29:56.970 --> 00:29:58.590
It changes over time.

00:29:58.590 --> 00:30:01.520
A particular civilizational
package, like law,

00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:03.450
it doesn't last as long as a language,

00:30:03.450 --> 00:30:05.670
but it can last much longer than a person.

00:30:05.670 --> 00:30:08.850
So the fact that Yaroslav
got the law together

00:30:08.850 --> 00:30:11.520
has meaning, which goes
well beyond his lifetime,

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:13.050
deep into the history of Lithuania.

00:30:13.050 --> 00:30:15.420
Centuries later, when Lithuanians

00:30:15.420 --> 00:30:17.220
are gonna be writing their grand statutes,

00:30:17.220 --> 00:30:19.560
which starts in the 16th century,

00:30:19.560 --> 00:30:21.510
when they write their
statutes, three of them,

00:30:21.510 --> 00:30:24.930
they're gonna be using this
language, Chancery Slavonic.

00:30:24.930 --> 00:30:26.490
In turn, it's gonna have more words

00:30:26.490 --> 00:30:28.050
from their part of the world and so on,

00:30:28.050 --> 00:30:32.100
but this civilizational
package long outlasts

00:30:32.100 --> 00:30:33.860
the actual Kyivan Rus'.

00:30:33.860 --> 00:30:36.887
So the last big thing we have to do,

00:30:36.887 --> 00:30:39.480
we've gotten Volodymyr to Yaroslav,

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:41.010
Yaroslav to the end of Rus'.

00:30:41.010 --> 00:30:42.660
Now we have to get to Lithuania.

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:43.980
What is Lithuania?

00:30:43.980 --> 00:30:45.300
And how could Lithuania be so, I mean,

00:30:45.300 --> 00:30:48.180
isn't Lithuania just this tiny country?

00:30:48.180 --> 00:30:50.430
It's this tiny country
filled with Baltic speakers?

00:30:50.430 --> 00:30:51.263
How can it?

00:30:51.263 --> 00:30:53.640
It was the biggest country
in Europe, my friends.

00:30:53.640 --> 00:30:56.670
It was the biggest country
in Europe at the time.

00:30:56.670 --> 00:30:59.700
And it emerged, as
countries often emerged,

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:02.284
because of pressure from two directions.

00:31:02.284 --> 00:31:05.160
The Lithuanian state consolidated,

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:08.640
because of pressure from the west,

00:31:08.640 --> 00:31:10.860
in the form of Christianity.

00:31:10.860 --> 00:31:13.680
Now a very aggressive, pointed pressure

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:16.170
in the form of crusades.

00:31:16.170 --> 00:31:18.270
A few centuries earlier,
when we're talking about

00:31:18.270 --> 00:31:21.480
the Franks, and Poland,
and Moravia, and so on,

00:31:21.480 --> 00:31:23.160
that's a more gentle pressure.

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:24.480
You know, we want you to convert.

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:26.589
Perhaps you'll be a little
bit subordinate to us.

00:31:26.589 --> 00:31:31.589
We're now in the 14th century
in the era of crusades,

00:31:32.760 --> 00:31:37.440
and the Lithuanians
were subject to violent,

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:39.930
forcible conversion.

00:31:39.930 --> 00:31:41.980
By that I mean, all the men were killed

00:31:43.950 --> 00:31:46.800
and the women and children
were taken and baptized.

00:31:46.800 --> 00:31:48.810
That's what the Teutonic Knights did.

00:31:48.810 --> 00:31:51.480
So pressure from the west,

00:31:51.480 --> 00:31:53.790
the Teutonic Knights had
wiped out the Prussians.

00:31:53.790 --> 00:31:55.740
I realize there's still
a place called Prussia,

00:31:55.740 --> 00:31:58.560
but the place called
Prussia today takes its name

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:01.950
from an earlier people who
spoke a Baltic language,

00:32:01.950 --> 00:32:03.420
similar to Lithuanian.

00:32:03.420 --> 00:32:06.570
These people were exterminated
by the Teutonic Knights.

00:32:06.570 --> 00:32:08.250
They no longer existed.

00:32:08.250 --> 00:32:09.930
And as that was happening,

00:32:09.930 --> 00:32:11.280
the groups of Baltic speakers

00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:12.690
that are called the Lithuanians

00:32:12.690 --> 00:32:14.940
managed to consolidate a state.

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:17.280
So they were consolidating
because of pressure

00:32:17.280 --> 00:32:18.113
from the west.

00:32:18.113 --> 00:32:20.790
And also, as we'll get
to, they consolidated

00:32:20.790 --> 00:32:23.070
because of what the
Mongols did in the south.

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:25.890
So faced with pressure from the west,

00:32:25.890 --> 00:32:28.057
the Lithuanian state in
the early 14th century,

00:32:28.057 --> 00:32:31.200
in the 13 hundreds, was able to move south

00:32:31.200 --> 00:32:34.860
from its base around Vilnius
into what's now Belarus,

00:32:34.860 --> 00:32:37.836
and deep into what's now Ukraine.

00:32:37.836 --> 00:32:39.840
And so, as they were
pressed from the west,

00:32:39.840 --> 00:32:42.270
they took advantage of
what the Mongols had done

00:32:42.270 --> 00:32:43.103
in the east.

00:32:43.103 --> 00:32:44.670
It might help, although, you know,

00:32:44.670 --> 00:32:46.740
in the kind in a kind of Christian
dominated historiography,

00:32:46.740 --> 00:32:48.120
this would never be put this way,

00:32:48.120 --> 00:32:50.550
to think of the Teutonic
Knights and the Mongols

00:32:50.550 --> 00:32:54.030
as arriving at about the
same time, which they did,

00:32:54.030 --> 00:32:56.190
and their arrival at about the same time

00:32:56.190 --> 00:32:58.507
creating the conditions
in which a Lithuania

00:32:58.507 --> 00:33:01.890
could face a challenge and
respond to that challenge

00:33:01.890 --> 00:33:04.560
by gathering up
territories from the south,

00:33:04.560 --> 00:33:07.350
from Rus, and becoming the
biggest state in Europe,

00:33:07.350 --> 00:33:08.860
which it was.

00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:11.940
So what do we know about Lithuania?

00:33:11.940 --> 00:33:16.710
The Lithuanians, so I talked
earlier about the math,

00:33:16.710 --> 00:33:19.320
the math of slavery and paganism.

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:22.048
The Lithuanians were the
last holdouts in this.

00:33:22.048 --> 00:33:25.110
They were the last major
pagan group in Europe.

00:33:25.110 --> 00:33:28.560
They were the last ones who
were able not to be enslaved

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:30.180
more than they enslaved others.

00:33:30.180 --> 00:33:33.750
They were using slave labor of
others in their countryside.

00:33:33.750 --> 00:33:37.448
They raided Rus' for slaves,
they raided Poland for slaves,

00:33:37.448 --> 00:33:39.540
they also raided their Baltic,

00:33:39.540 --> 00:33:41.160
their pagan neighbors for slaves.

00:33:41.160 --> 00:33:43.320
So long as they had pagan neighbors.

00:33:43.320 --> 00:33:45.270
They brought in tens
of thousands of people

00:33:45.270 --> 00:33:48.870
to work as slaves in their agriculture.

00:33:48.870 --> 00:33:52.800
We know that they traded
timber, and furs, and grain,

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:56.340
and wax and honey for iron products.

00:33:56.340 --> 00:33:58.740
We know that they turned
a corner in their own

00:33:58.740 --> 00:34:01.500
agricultural planning in
the early 14th century

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:03.455
under their most important ruler,

00:34:03.455 --> 00:34:06.480
who I may not have put down, Gediminas.

00:34:06.480 --> 00:34:07.650
Is he there?

00:34:07.650 --> 00:34:08.866
He's there?

00:34:08.866 --> 00:34:09.699
Okay.

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:13.627
So under Gediminas, who
ruled from 1315 to 1343,

00:34:13.627 --> 00:34:17.280
they started moving away from slavery

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:19.350
and towards colonization,

00:34:19.350 --> 00:34:23.100
where they would accept
the rules of local,

00:34:23.100 --> 00:34:25.406
they would kind of control
land rather than people.

00:34:25.406 --> 00:34:28.050
So in a way it's the
same kind of transition

00:34:28.050 --> 00:34:31.230
you see earlier in Rus', control
land, rather than people,

00:34:31.230 --> 00:34:33.930
accept basically the rules
that already existed.

00:34:33.930 --> 00:34:36.184
And then try to tax.

00:34:36.184 --> 00:34:40.890
It's Gediminas who moves
into what is now Rus'.

00:34:40.890 --> 00:34:42.060
What was their religion?

00:34:42.060 --> 00:34:43.950
Very briefly about this,

00:34:43.950 --> 00:34:46.590
we know a lot more about
it because their paganism

00:34:46.590 --> 00:34:48.573
lasted for another four centuries.

00:34:49.890 --> 00:34:53.820
And many people had contact
with them, many Christians,

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:55.560
many Muslims, many Jews
had contacts with them

00:34:55.560 --> 00:34:56.550
over the centuries.

00:34:56.550 --> 00:34:59.640
There were Christian churches
in Vilnius the whole time.

00:34:59.640 --> 00:35:00.473
Why?

00:35:00.473 --> 00:35:03.420
Because if you're a
tolerant, prosperous regime,

00:35:03.420 --> 00:35:05.430
you need to have traders
coming from other places

00:35:05.430 --> 00:35:07.347
and you have to make sure
they have churches, right?

00:35:07.347 --> 00:35:11.898
And additionally, just to make
sure this is always clear,

00:35:11.898 --> 00:35:13.620
this story is gonna end with

00:35:13.620 --> 00:35:15.600
the Lithuanian rulers converting,

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:18.930
but the Lithuanian rulers are
always ruling over a country

00:35:18.930 --> 00:35:20.520
which is majority Christian.

00:35:20.520 --> 00:35:23.220
Because most of the people
who are in Lithuania

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:25.410
are in what is now Belarus, and then later

00:35:25.410 --> 00:35:28.350
in what is now Ukraine, i.e.
they're Eastern Christians.

00:35:28.350 --> 00:35:31.320
So the whole time this is a regime where

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:34.440
the rulers are pagans, and the
ruling families are pagans,

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:38.610
but most of the population
are actually Christians.

00:35:38.610 --> 00:35:40.140
So when I talk about this religion,

00:35:40.140 --> 00:35:42.750
this is the religion of the Baltic core,

00:35:42.750 --> 00:35:46.200
which then spreads out and
tolerates Christianity.

00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:49.203
They make no attempt at
converting the Christians at all.

00:35:50.190 --> 00:35:53.720
So we know that the grand
duke was also the high priest.

00:35:53.720 --> 00:35:58.720
We know that the priests
were priests of sacrifice,

00:35:59.070 --> 00:36:00.540
as in the Slavic lands.

00:36:00.540 --> 00:36:02.490
We know what some of the
most important gods were,

00:36:02.490 --> 00:36:03.900
who were familiar figures already.

00:36:03.900 --> 00:36:06.933
They had a version of Perun,
who was called Perknas.

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:09.810
In general, if you just add us to the end,

00:36:09.810 --> 00:36:10.980
you'll get a Lithuanian word.

00:36:10.980 --> 00:36:14.430
So like, okay, doesn't always work.

00:36:14.430 --> 00:36:16.920
Doesn't always work.

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:19.220
But the Lithuanian version
of Perun was called Perknas.

00:36:19.220 --> 00:36:22.530
Other important gods were

00:36:22.530 --> 00:36:24.960
Andai, who was associated with water,

00:36:24.960 --> 00:36:28.890
Teliavel, who was associated
with like a Hephaestus figure,

00:36:28.890 --> 00:36:30.480
associated with the smithy.

00:36:30.480 --> 00:36:35.340
But as with the Slavic paganism,
the gods were not separate.

00:36:35.340 --> 00:36:38.310
This is much more animistic,
it's much more a religion

00:36:38.310 --> 00:36:43.310
where everything is in some
sense animated by divinity.

00:36:43.860 --> 00:36:45.747
So trees were venerated.

00:36:45.747 --> 00:36:50.277
Specific groves of trees
regardless as important.

00:36:50.277 --> 00:36:52.812
In specific groves of trees,

00:36:52.812 --> 00:36:56.790
the dead would be burned as a sacrifice.

00:36:56.790 --> 00:36:59.970
Specific springs and rivers
and rocks were also important.

00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:03.690
The Lithuanians, like the
Slavs, also didn't have temples

00:37:03.690 --> 00:37:06.390
until they made contact with Christians.

00:37:06.390 --> 00:37:07.620
And then they began to build temples,

00:37:07.620 --> 00:37:12.620
it appears, as a kind of
borrowing from the Christians.

00:37:12.690 --> 00:37:17.040
We know that they divined
omens from the behavior of,

00:37:17.040 --> 00:37:18.660
some of them still do, from the behavior

00:37:18.660 --> 00:37:20.460
of horses and snakes.

00:37:20.460 --> 00:37:22.890
We know that after
victories they sacrificed

